\begin_layout Abstract
Principles from Information Economics lead to a conjecture that three distinct
 modes exist for competitive differentiation based on information.
 Differentiated access affords informational asymmetries to  competitors
 who enjoy it.
 Marketplace participants see information in evidence that competitors miss
 through differentiated insights.
 Differentiated ability to act occurs in superior abilities to transform
 information into utility.
 This can be characterized by a formalism with Decision Analysis at its
 core.
 Other disciplines including theory of evidence, information theory, and
 competency-focused frameworks for differentiation also  contribute.
 The theory of evidence produces a more-complete characterization of uncertainty
 than traditional Bayesian techniques.
 Information theory provides for a rigorous, abstract approach to quantifying
 information and uncertainty.
 Mining a textbook case study exercises the formalism to quantify returns
 from information, and to analogously corroborate our conjecture.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% Enter your abstract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That we operate in an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Information-Age Economy
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

has been a cliché for a generation (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shapiro1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Peter Drucker anticipated as early as the late 1950s the emergence of 
\shape italic
knowledge work
\shape default
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wartzman2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 He subsequently foresaw that, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledge 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle$
\end_inset

becomes
\begin_inset Formula $\rangle$
\end_inset

 a more-crucial economic resource than land, labor, or financial assets,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) leading to what he called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

post-capitalist society
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Porter and Millar (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) observed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the information revolution sweeping through our economy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the mid-1980s.
 They provided heuristic descriptions of informational impacts in terms
 of existing value-chain frameworks for the analysis of strategy.
 Although this early work did not anticipate early-21st-century emergent
 operating models, likely strategic impacts were described.
 These included improved operational efficiencies, more-tailored responsiveness
 to market pulls, and adaptively shifting competitive scope.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uncertainty is the opposite side of the information and knowledge coin (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Briggs2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 It is an inescapable aspect of business environments.
 Organizations' approaches to uncertainty can lead either to differentiation
 or to demise (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lynch2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Entirely new business models have emerged focusing on curation and exploitation
 of information and data (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Redman2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Such models that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

have as their business the production and distribution of knowledge and
 information, rather than the production of things, ...
 have moved into the center of the economy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision analysis (DA) is a core business competency guiding the transformation
 of information and uncertainty into economic value (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Spetzler2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The centrality of information's role in the economy amplify's DA's importance.
 If information is indeed a more-important business asset than land, labor,
 and financial assets historically have been, then DA's position perhaps
 approaches other more-prominent business-management disciplines such as
 operations and supply-chain management.
 The ability to parse information and uncertainty — and efficiently and
 effectively act thereupon — becomes an important determinant of competitiveness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We undertake here the articulation of a formalism for the characterization
 of information's contribution to competitive differentiation.
 We begin with a conjecture arising from Information Economics.
 Specifically, three distinct modes of information-based advantage occur.
 Differentiated access arises from information others lack.
 Differentiated insights result from seeing things in the evidentiary corpora
 overlooked by others.
 Superior capabilities to extract value from information possibly available
 to others exemplifies differentiated ability to act.
 Organizations distinguishing themselves via information exploitation apply
 these modes individually or in combination to realize superior return on
 information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our formalism is grounded in a 
\emph on
Generalized Decision-Analysis Problem
\emph default
.
 A novel formulation introduced here emphasizes attributing value to information.
 Specifically, the optimum decision produces the greatest expected net return
 of all options given a set of consistently-framed scenarios directly coupled
 by alternative courses of action and probabilistically-determined outcomes.
 These courses of action represent distinct decisions by active decision-makers
 in our scenarios.
 They are deterministic branches in contexts within which many aspects of
 outcomes are probabilistic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mechanically, our approach employs the 
\emph on
Theory of Evidence
\emph default
 (ToE), a generalization of the commonly-employed Bayesian-analysis approach
 to DA.
 Two aspects of ToE recommend themselves to our endeavor.
 First, traditional Bayesian theory under many circumstances can lead to
 overstatement of the degree of certainty underlying a scenario.
 Relaxing selected Bayesian axioms, ToE allows a mechanism of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

partial belief
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, by which evidence can be treated as inconclusive.
 Secondly, traditional Bayesian theory can attribute preferential influence
 to prior probabilities.
 ToE combines evidence in a fashion that is more-symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We overlay our modes of differentiation onto strategy frameworks focused
 on organizational competencies.
 The Dynamic Capabilities framework by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the Adaptivity-Advantage method by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide structure for exploring differentiating consequences of our modes
 of information-derived advantage.
 Each mode bears on distinct phases and components of these competency-based
 frameworks.
 This ties our information-differentiation modes to contexts of competitive
 differentiation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A textbook case study related to petroleum-extraction decision illustrates
 the framework.
 A parameter study demonstrates the relationship between uncertainty — represent
ed by either a Bayesian probability distribution or a ToE basic-belief assignmen
t — and expected net-return from a consistently-framed decision scenario.
 Aspects of the case study corroborate the conjecture about modes of information
-differentiation.
 Contrasts between expected-net returns employing Bayesian and ToE frameworks
 for uncertainty are apparent.
 This is corroborated by information-theoretic (entropy) comparisons.
 In particular, framing uncertainty using ToE leads lower expected-net returns.
 This is consistent with the assertion of greater perception of certainty
 when employing Bayesian approaches than with ToE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study defers consideration of key questions related to information-based
 differentiation.
 First, relative return on information provides the present criterion for
 informationally-derived advantage.
 This might not be sufficient for all scenarios.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Phlips1988"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Laffont1989"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 examine market-equilibria conditions in information-driven markets.
 Extending our formalism to such competitive scenarios will produce a more-compl
ete view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Drucker's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 characterization of an information-intensive economy as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

post-capitalist
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 represents another unaddressed complexity.
 Mainstream microeconomic theory explains a 
\emph on
material economy
\emph default
, in which resource scarcity drives resource allocation.
 If information itself is a key asset, an 
\emph on
ethereal economy
\emph default
 alternatively occurs.
 Resource constraints in the ethereal economy tend to be talent-related
 rather than material.
 Moreover, information 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

products
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be simultaneously used by multiple customers without constraining the
 use by any individual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How some microeconomic mechanisms play out in an ethereal marketplace is
 unclear.
 For example, price-elasticity, one of markets' principle mechanisms for
 self-regulation, results from degrees of scarcity and necessity in conjunction
 with each other.
 Scarcity, in particular, ceases to be a natural constraint in the case
 of ethereal goods.
 Our case study more-directly explores informational control over the material
 economy than over the ethereal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, our framework at this juncture remains epistemically imprecise.
 We knowingly conflate distinct entities such as knowledge, information,
 competency, and data.
 A more-rigorous epistemic framework will improve the descriptive power
 of the formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Toolkit for Characterizing Differentiated Decision-Making
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We introduce here our framework for characterizing opportunities for competitive
 advantage.
 It fuses together five distinct practices or disciplines.
 We explain their integration progressively as we introduce each.
 A coherent, holistic description of information's contribution to differentiati
on occurs.
 The DA discipline occupies a central, unifying role.
 These introductions also contain extensive surveys of prior relevant literature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Information Economics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field of Information Economics studies the attribution of value to informati
on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Birchler1999,Brunnermeier2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is most-commonly applied within the context of financial markets.
 It explains for example how bid-ask prices reveal market counter-parties
 proprietary positions with respect to risk and other objectives.
 Common theories of financial-market operations, such as the Efficient-Market
 Hypothesis, are among the more-familiar applications of information economics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discipline of information economics resides at the nexus of four other
 disciplines.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Info-Econ Position"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 depicts this intersection.
 First, information theory provides mechanisms to precisely quantify information.
 This includes two loosely-related branches.
 Quantitative information theory was originally developed for communications
 theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shannon1948,Gallagher1968,Cover1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Borrowing concepts from the physical discipline of thermodynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ben-Naim2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, it provides an abstract view of information as a quantity.
 Semantic information theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chomsky2014,Zhong2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explains linguistic and psychological aspects of information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Game Theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Myerson1991,Papayoanou2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explains counterparties' behaviors in competitive situations, often involving
 incomplete information.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Elementary Game
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 assumes a prominent role in the treatment by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Birchler1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The elementary game postulates about counterparties' decisions whether
 or not to play a game based upon their informational states.
 Decisions are made based on expected outcomes in the presence of uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Position of Information Economics with respect to related disciplines.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Info-Econ Position"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
