\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concepts from microeconomics build upon information theory and game theory
 to explain equilibria conditions within markets involving multiple counterparti
es'.
 As usual, equilibrium is reached when bidding and asking counterparties'
 positions converge to mutually agreed-to price points.
 Information-economics theory here does not distinguish between the etherial
 and material markets referred to in the introduction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, behavioral economics has recently begun to influence information
 economics.
 One of the field's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

founders
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 D.
 Kahneman describes in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kahneman2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 the use of decision games resembling the Elementary Game to characterize
 participants' understandings of probabilities.
 Prospect theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kahneman1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 formally extends the resulting concepts into psychological explanations
 for decision makers' views of risk and utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information modeling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Samuelson2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 features prominently within the information-economics toolkit.
 Information modeling employs concepts resembling those at the heart of
 decision analysis and theory of evidence, to be visited subsequently.
 First, it draws heavily from Bayesian theory, also foundational for decision
 analysis.
 Its representation of information dovetails well into ToE's framework.
 Both support ambiguity in states of belief.
 The machineries of the respective methods are well-positioned for integration
 and convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now a central information-economics principal leads to the fundamental conjectur
e of this study.
 Specifically,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
vspace{-12pt}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{quotation}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent 
\backslash
textcolor{Night}{
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The utility value of a piece of information is the difference between the
 expected utility a decision-maker can achieve by choosing the best action
 
\backslash
textit{conditional} on the information received, and the expected utility
 from the action that is best in the 
\backslash
textit{absence} of the information.
 The money value is the amount of money that renders the decision-maker
 
\backslash
textit{indifferent} to both.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

} 
\backslash
cite{Birchler1999}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{quotation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
vspace{-12pt}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Our three modes of differentiation occur either explicitly or by implication.
 Differentiated access — possessing a piece of information that a counter
 party lacks — explicitly appears.
 A counter party with a 
\emph on
relevant
\emph default
 information advantage by extension enjoys an opportunity-realization advantage.
 This is information asymmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information-insights differentiation appears by implication.
 Both counterparties might share access to the same evidentiary corpus —
 or body of information — about the decision with which they are confronted.
 One however sees something in that evidentiary corpus that one or more
 counter party does not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Michael Lewis' 
\emph on
Moneyball 
\emph default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lewis2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, a mid-2000s popular-nonfiction treatment American professional baseball,
 illustrates.
 The featured club employed a distinct model for attributing value to individual
 baseball players contributions.
 This differentiated insight conferred considerable advantage in playing
 competition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differences in insights from a common evidentiary corpus may arise from
 a variety of circumstances.
 The field of organizational epistemology (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vonKrogh1994,Seirafi2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) systematically examines how organizations translate information into actionabl
e knowledge.
 Prospect-theoretic considerations may inhibit — or sometimes even fortuitously
 enhance — an organizations' ability to recognize value opportunities.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Denrell2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hot-Stove
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 affect, under which risk-aversion inhibits organizations' abilities to
 learn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pisano2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 makes passing mention of how 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

innovative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 organizations might cultivate counterproductive 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 through undisciplined, indiscriminate learning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ability-to-act differentiation also appears explicitly.
 Different market participants enjoy different utility-realization capabilities.
 A distinct branch of business strategy studies organizations' abilities
 to effectively respond to new information.
 Teece's Dynamic Capabilities framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Reeves' Adaptivity Advantage 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 exemplify.
 For instance, an organization might avail itself of an opportunity for
 differentiated return by responding first to information about an opportunity.
 Alternatively, another might realize superior return through responding
 more-efficiently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Decision Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision analysis (DA) is a business discipline focused characterizing the
 quality of decisions within the context of uncertainty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Spetzler2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Conceptually congruent with Information Economics, DA seeks to identify
 discrete actions yielding the optimum return in a precisely-framed scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our consideration of DA here begins by proffering a generalized statement
 of its central problem.
 Given this study's central conjecture, we emphasize attributing value to
 information driving decisions.
 We then review a methodology that enjoys near-paradigmatic status in the
 DA-practitioner community.
 Finally we give consideration to the implications of behavioral economics
 for DA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Generalized Decision-Analysis Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A generalized mathematical statement articulates the DA problem.
 Specifically, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}=\\
=\arg\max_{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}}\bigg\{\Big({\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
x\in\mathscr{X}\\
y\in\mathcal{Y}\\
z\in\mathcal{Z}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(x,y,z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}\big)\Big)\\
-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}\big)\bigg\}\text{,}\label{Gen Opt Decision}
\end{multline}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
\mathcal{R}^{\text{opt}}={\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
x\in\mathscr{X}\\
y\in\mathcal{Y}\\
z\in\mathcal{Z}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(x,y,z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\\
-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\text{, and}\label{Gen Opt Return}
\end{multline}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{V}_{\text{info}}=\mathcal{R}^{\text{opt}}-\mathcal{R}^{]\text{nominal}}\text{.}\label{Gen Info Value}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\boldsymbol{D}}$
\end_inset

 denotes the set of all possible decisions within our framed scenario, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 the expected net return conditioned on the particular set of decisions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{d}\in\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is the costs incurred with acting according to that particular decision
 set.
 The uncertainty is characterized by probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 in terms random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X},\,\mathscr{Y},\,\text{and}\,\mathscr{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Explicitly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{P}:\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}\times\mathscr{Z}\mapsto\left[0,1\right]\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

In terms of our conjecture, variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}$
\end_inset

 is the additional information obtained through selection some decision
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{d}\in\boldsymbol{D}$
\end_inset

 at a cost of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\left(\mathfrak{d}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

 represents the additional information resulting from differentiated insights.
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the inherent phenomenology determining the returns.
 We attribute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\text{info}}$
\end_inset

 information value by comparing the return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^{\text{opt}}$
\end_inset

 arising from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}$
\end_inset

, the optimum decision, to some nominal baseline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mechanisms suggested by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 indicate how uncertainty is resolved.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a joint probability distribution in the traditional
 Bayesian sense.
 We see in the next section that under ToE things become more-complicated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nonetheless, adding information associated with differentiated access or
 insights allows one to consider returns in terms of conditional probabilities,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(z\mid x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 for example.
 If our phenomenological variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 is not independent of the other variables,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{P}\nvDash\mathcal{\left(\mathcal{Z}\perp\mathscr{X}\text{,}\mathscr{Y}\right)\text{,}}
\]

\end_inset

then conditioning often has the affect of reducing its uncertainty.
 This in turn reduces the variability of the range of possible outcomes,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We more-rigorously consider affects of conditioning in a subsequent section
 on information quantification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) might induce in an operations analysts the inclination to apply optimization-s
earch techniques to its solution.
 Although not impossible, such an attempt might prove challenging.
 The decision-optimization rule (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is discretely non-convex.
 The presence of the decision factors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

 introduce discrete, deterministic branches within the probability space.
 Analysis cases must be conditioned on each distinct decisional configuration
 represented by set of decisions 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Armed with the framework of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) – (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Info Value"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we can now think about differentiated returns associated with distinct
 modes of information-based differentiation.
 First consider the scenario of differentiated access.
 The increase in expected net returns arising from making some optimum set
 of decisions 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}$
\end_inset

 straightforwardly becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
\mathcal{R}^{\text{diff access}}-\mathcal{R}^{\text{nominal}}=\\
={\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
x\in\mathscr{X}\\
z\in\mathcal{Z}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(x,z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\\
-{\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
z\in\mathcal{Z}\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\big)\Big)\\
-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\\
+\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\big)\text{.}\label{eq: Diff Returns from Access}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

At a marginal cost of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\right)-\mathcal{C}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\right)$
\end_inset

 we realize an increase in marginal expected net-returns.
 Explicitly, our marginal return becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{M}^{\text{diff access}}=\dfrac{\left(\begin{gathered}{\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
x\in\mathscr{X}\\
z\in\mathcal{Z}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(x,z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\\
-{\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
z\in\mathcal{Z}\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\big)\Big)
\end{gathered}
\right)}{\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{nominal}}\big)}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar logic applies to differentiated insights.
 The difference being that margin for differentiated insights is undefined.
 Conditioning on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 does not cost us in the sense of incurring a cost associated with some
 decision 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{d}\in\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The excess returns from differentiated ability to act arises from the return
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 itself.
 Specifically,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\mathcal{R}^{\text{diff ability}}-\mathcal{R}^{\text{nominal}}=\\
={\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
x\in\mathscr{X}\\
z\in\mathcal{Z}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(x,z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}^{\text{differentiated}}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\\
-{\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
x\in\mathscr{X}\\
z\in\mathcal{Z}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(x,z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}^{\text{nominal}}\big(z;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\text{.}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

We assume here that both organizations operate given identical evidentiary
 corpora.
 The expend substantially similar amounts in acquisition of information.
 The difference arises from their ability transform information into utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Common Decision-Analysis Method Employed within the Practitioner Community
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DA-practitioner community methodologically realizes these concepts using
 techniques originally described separately by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Raiffa1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Howard2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The associated 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

playbook
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 enjoys enjoy near-paradigmatic status.
 The common methodology focuses on decision-framing.
 Framing consists of analysis of distinct scenarios, which are coupled by
 discrete decisions and probabilistic chances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates.
 This example comes from a textbook petroleum-extraction case study to be
 considered in-detail, later.
 We focus here the structure represented by Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and explore its contents, later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision trees are a commonly-used tool for framing of decisions.
 We construct decision trees from three distinct types of vertices (nodes).
 Square-shaped vertices represent deterministic branches in which representing
 a decision-maker's deliberate action.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 contains only binary — Yes-versus-No — decisions.
 This need not always be the case.
 The edges emanating from decision nodes are labeled with the decision options
 and with the 
\emph on
direct
\emph default
 costs associated each.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Illustration of decision-tree framing of decision scenarios.
 (After 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Strat1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/190425 Oil-Drilling Decision-Tree template.png
	lyxscale 20
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Round-shaped vertices are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 nodes.
 These represent discrete, probabilistic branches in our probability space.
 Graph edges emanating from chance nodes are labeled with the distinct state,
 and the probability of its occurrence.
 Hexagonal vertices are outcome vertices.
 These correspond to the final state in a given scenario.
 Each is labeled with its corresponded expected net return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each left-to-right path through the tree — from initial decision to ultimate
 outcome — represents a distinct scenario.
 The scenarios are framed so that they are coupled together via deterministic
 decision nodes and probabilistic chance nodes.
 The left-most chance nodes are labeled with marginal probabilities.
 Proceeding left to right, each subsequent chance node is labeled with probabili
ties conditioned on the preceding chance-node branches.
 Employing classical Bayesian analysis, conditioning and marginalization
 occur according to standard practices in categorical-data analysis (e.g.,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Agresti2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 We discover in the next section that ToE analysis is more-complicated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The costs and outcomes are represented according to Time-Value-of-Money
 (TVoM) principles (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brealy2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Decision-framing requires that costs and returns be referenced to the same
 point in time.
 They therefore are net-present values (NPVs) referenced to point in time
 with meaningful business purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Net-expected returns are aggregated right-to-left.
 Expected net returns at chance vertices are the probability-weighted NPVs
 of those adjacent to the right.
 Aggregation at decision nodes occurs by discretely selecting the right-adjacent
 vertex with the greatest corresponding net-expected return.
 To reiterate, the decision nodes introduce the discrete non-convexity in
 the probability space of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Decision Analysis and Prospect Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question might arise regarding the application of Behavioral Economics
 — Prospect Theory, in particular 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kahneman1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 — to decision analysis.
 Limited rationality of decision makers represents a topic of extensive
 contemporary interest.
 Why, for example, might or might one not factor prospect-theoretic consideratio
ns into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)? Four considerations are offered here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, one might consider attempting to incorporate an individual's or an
 organization's idiosyncratic utility functions into our return function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

.
 This in general would be difficult.
 Identification of idiosyncratic utilities would require challenging psychometri
c or sociometric analysis, for which the the net-improvement in informational
 value would be uncertain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, within the analytical sciences, establishing objective performance
 bounds represents common practices.
 The use of the Cramer-Rao Lower Bound in statistical analysis represents
 an analogy (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kay1993,Hogg2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Analysis following establishment of a theoretical best bound focuses on
 diagnosing root causes of variances.
 Addressable root causes are prioritized according to difficulty and significanc
e.
 These could, of course, included prospect-theoretic challenges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thirdly, framing decisions in rational and objective terms constitutes the
 principal goal of DA.
 Kahneman modeled human cognition using two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

systems
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kahneman2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

System 1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 characterizes an intuitive, reflexive mode of decision-making.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

System 2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 describes the deliberate, rational mode.
 Kahneman's essential conclusion was that human decision makers 
\emph on
are capable
\emph default
 of objective decision-making in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

System-2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 mode.
 This is however effortful and physiologically-demanding.
 DA is about forcing decision-makers into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

System-2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 modes for decisions that are sufficiently important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, defining a formalized methodology for comparative 
\emph on
return on information
\emph default
 represents the principle focus of our central conjecture and its exploration.
 Understanding obstacles to achieving objectively-identified, theoretically-best
 outcomes is related aspect.
 Many individuals and organizations no doubt encounter barriers arising
 from prospect-theoretic challenges.
 Diagnosing these — and if possible, remedying them as well — represents
 a potential outgrowth of this study.
 The diagnostic process requires separation of prospect-theoretic challenges
 from theoretically-optimum outcomes.
 We first establish the later using the framework of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Info Value"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Theory of Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Theory of Evidence (ToE) — also referred to a Dempster-Shafer Theory
 — seeks to represent uncertainty in a more-general fashion than the traditional
 Bayesian approach to probability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shafer1976,Smets1994,Salicone2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It accomplishes this principally by expanding the domain over which probability
 masses are assigned.
 ToE can be formulated as a generalization of Bayes Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Originally articulated as a complete theory by Glen Shafer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shafer1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, ToE was studied extensively as a probabilistic-reasoning framework for
 artificial-intelligence applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Its application to DA was also described 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Strat1994,Smets2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The metrology community more-recently adopted a ToE framework as a replacement
 for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

accuracy-and-error
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 paradigm for characterizing uncertainty in scientific and engineering measureme
nts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Salicone2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Commonalities with fuzzy logic have also been observed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Skalna2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, portending the potential for convergence of the two disciplines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, ToE seems apropos due to similarities it shares with information
 modeling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Samuelson2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 from Information Economics.
 A full reconciliation of the respective methods lies beyond the scope of
 the present study.
 Nonetheless, we lay the groundwork here for such a subsequent effort.
 The resulting payoff would be a tighter alignment of DA with Information
 Economics, leading to more-general approaches to information-valuation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following seeks to imbue an intuitive sense through illustrating the
 pattern of reasoning under ToE.
 We next concisely survey its mechanics.
 We then review approaches to its applications to decision analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Probabilistic Reasoning under the Theory of Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for purposes of illustration.
 The graph represents a notional 
\emph on
Frame of Discernment 
\emph default
(FoD) corresponding to a two-dimensional, binary probability space.
 The FoD encompasses all propositions to which measure of belief can be
 attributed.
 Distinct propositions to which finite (nonzero) belief is attributed are
 
\emph on
focal elements
\emph default
.
 The 
\emph on
core
\emph default
 includes all such focal elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How does ToE differ from Bayesian theory? In the latter we can only attribute
 belief to the distinct 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

atomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 propositions.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 this is constrained to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}\bigr)=\Bigl\{\bigl\{\left(x,y\right)\bigr\},\bigl\{\left(\bar{x},y\right)\bigr\},\bigl\{\left(x,\bar{y}\right)\bigr\},\bigl\{\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\bigr\}\Bigr\}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

Within such a regime, complete uncertainty is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{\mathcal{P}}\Big(\big\{\xi,\eta\big\}\Big)=\frac{1}{\bigl|\bigl(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}\bigr)\bigr|}\quad\forall\,\big\{\xi,\eta\big\}\in\bigl(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}\bigr)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

For the illustration of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 — a binary, two-dimensional probability space — the cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl|\bigl(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}\bigr)\bigr|=4$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, we assert that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{\mathcal{P}}\Big(\big\{\xi,\eta\big\}\Big)=\frac{1}{4}\quad\forall\,\big\{\xi,\eta\big\}\in\bigl(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}\bigr)
\]

\end_inset

under complete uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Illustrative probability-mass assignment over a frame of discernment under
 the Theory of Evidence (after 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Illustrative ToE BBA"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/m_Ωˣʸ_heatmap.png
	lyxscale 10
	width 13cm
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reasoning under ToE admits that a given evidentiary corpus might not support
 any of the propositions in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}\bigr)$
\end_inset

 with a degree of confidence anywhere near 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 It therefore provides for a mechanism called 
\emph on
partial belief
\emph default
.
 A closely-related concept of 
\emph on
vacuous belief
\emph default
 represents the most-extreme form of partial belief.
 Vacuous belief articulates a state of belief along the lines of, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

One of the above but cannot tell which.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Partial belief ranges across various degrees of vacuity, ranging from complete
 certainty that one of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

atomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 propositions is true, to the complete vacuity referred-to above.
 Smets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1988,Smets1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 includes a provision for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

None of the above
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 This lies beyond our present scope.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Returning to the illustration in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
basic belief assignments
\emph default
 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\mathcal{P}\Big(\big\{\left(x,y\right)\big\}\Big)=\mathcal{P}\Big(\big\{\left(x,\bar{y}\right)\big\}\Big)=0.1\text{,}\\
\mathcal{P}\Big(\big\{\left(\bar{x},y\right)\big\}\Big)=\mathcal{P}\Big(\big\{\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\big\}\Big)=0.3\text{, and}\\
\mathcal{P}\Bigg(\bigg\{\begin{gathered}\left(x,y\right),\left(x,\bar{y}\right),\\
\left(\bar{x},y\right),\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)
\end{gathered}
\bigg\}\Bigg)=0.2\text{.}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset

We thereby interpret the evidence as supporting the proposition 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

One of the above but cannot tell which
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with probability of 0.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Frame-of-Discernment illustration based on multi-resolution image analysis
 (from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prasad1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "DWT FoD Illustration"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../../Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/190620 INFORMS ADA/DWT Image-Decomposition Illustration.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	width 17cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This brings us to a key aspect of reasoning under ToE.
 Our frame of discernment — the total set of propositions to which one might
 assign some degree of belief — is the power set 
\begin_inset Formula $\wp$
\end_inset

 of the atomic propositions.
 In our Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustration, or 
\emph on
Bayesian
\emph default
 frame of discernment is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}=\bigg\{\begin{gathered}\left(x,y\right),\left(x,\bar{y}\right),\\
\left(\bar{x},y\right),\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)
\end{gathered}
\bigg\}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

The ToE frame of discernment in contrast is specified by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\Omega}}}^{\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y}}=\wp\Big(\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}\Big)
\]

\end_inset

 and includes all vertices in the directed graph in the Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, the traditional Bayesian-probability scenario is simply a special case
 of ToE.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 developed a 
\emph on
Generalized Bayesian Theorem
\emph default
 (GBT).
 The GBT extends the familiar framework of prior probabilities, likelihoods,
 and posterior probabilities to the more-general FoD 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is moreover accompanied by a 
\emph on
Conditional Cognitive Independence
\emph default
 framework for ascertaining the belief induced by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

independent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observations.
 The concepts bear some resemblance to work in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lindley1983"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, describing the reconciliation of probability distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bayesian frame of discernment represents only one specialization of
 the ToE frame of discernment.
 Fuzzy logic employs a method in which the frame of discernment is monotonic
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chow1997,Skalna2015,Salicone2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\mathcal{X}_{i}=\big\{ x_{1},\ldots,x_{i}\big\}\text{, and}\\
\mathcal{X}_{1}\subset\mathcal{X}_{2}\subset\ldots\mathcal{X}_{n}\equiv\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}\text{.}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset

This framework is referred to as 
\emph on
Possibility Theory
\emph default
.
 Its resemblance to ToE has led to movement towards the convergence of the
 two disciplines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-resolution analysis offers another example 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mallat1989"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Multi-resolution decompositions combine a monotonic decomposition of the
 frame of discernment with a partitioning.
 The monotonic component is referred to as the 
\emph on
approximation
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 Each
\emph on
 
\emph default
approximation is further partitioned into another constituent approximation
 and a 
\emph on
detail
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically, at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 scale,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\mathcal{A}_{n+1}=\mathcal{A}_{n}\cup\mathcal{D}_{n}\\
\text{such that}\quad\mathcal{A}_{n}\cap\mathcal{D}_{n}=\varnothing\text{.}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset

Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "DWT FoD Illustration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 contains a two-dimensional illustration from image-processing, a typical
 application 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prasad1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "DWT FoD Illustration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(c) contains the original image.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "DWT FoD Illustration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(b) shows its multi-resolution decomposition.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "DWT FoD Illustration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(a) shows the partition scheme for the frame of discernment.
 Researchers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tajeddini2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have in fact combined multi-resolution analysis with ToE for noise-cancellation
 purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How might evidence supporting partial belief might present itself in a practical
 context? Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Correlation multi-colinearity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates using a graphical representation of a correlation matrix.
 Pair-wise correlation values are indicated by the heat-map color scale
 applied to the graph edges.
 The graph contains three cliques of three tuples of variables with correlations
 of 0.9.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Graphical representation of a correlation matrix for data with considerable
 collinearity.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Correlation multi-colinearity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/correlation_graph_legend.png
	lyxscale 10
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such instances can be interpreted as cases in which the measurements do
 not clearly resolve differences between the underlying measurands.
 Perhaps the measurands themselves are indistinct.
 Maybe the measure is not robustly order-preserving.
 In any case, distinguishing between discrete measured features might not
 be altogether justified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Correlation multi-colinearity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, assigning our beliefs to the highly-collinear cliques —
\begin_inset Formula $\big\{ x_{0},x_{1},x_{2}\big\},\,\big\{ x_{3},x_{4},x_{5}\big\},\,\big\{ x_{6},x_{7},x_{8}\big\},\,\big\{ x_{9}\big\}$
\end_inset

 — might be more-justified than attributing belief to the individual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

atomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 propositions (features, variables).
 Principal-component analysis accomplishes this in a sense.
 Moreover, the unexplained variance (residuals) in a linear model might
 amount to belief vacuously attributed to the total feature set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}=\big\{ x_{1},\ldots,x_{9}\big\}$
\end_inset

; or to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

none of the above
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}\ni x=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Mechanics of the Theory of Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending Dempster's original method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dempster1967"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the combination of evidence, Shafer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shafer1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described a set of four systematically-interrelated quantities for characterizi
ng state of belief about propositions within the FoD.
 Both also described the combination of beliefs and evidence from distinct
 frames of discernment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Four particular quantities reside at the theory's heart.
 We usually elicit a basic-belief assignment (bba) 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}$
\end_inset

 on our frame of discernment 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}=\wp\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We populate it after the manner illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our bba satisfies the property
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\omega\in\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)=1\text{.}\label{eq: Unit-norm BBA}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the ToE equivalent to the conventional Bayesian axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mathcal{P}\big(\left\{ \omega\right\} \big)=1\text{,}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a probability-mass function on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

atomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (singleton) focal elements of our FoD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}$
\end_inset

 we calculate three other quantities.
 The 
\emph on
Belief Function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)=\sum_{\begin{gathered}\varpi\subset\omega\\
\varpi\ne\varnothing
\end{gathered}
}m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\left(\varpi\right)\text{.}\label{eq: Belief Function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\emph on
lower-probability
\emph default
 function.
 For a given proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\boldsymbol{\Omega}=\wp\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 aggregates all of the belief attributed to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 itself, as well as to any subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)=1\text{,}
\]

\end_inset

which indicates with certainty that any admissible proposition resides in
 the frame of discernment.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1988,Smets1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe a ToE generalization by which this constraint is relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This justifies the direction of the edges of the directed graph in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 A basic-belief assignment attributed to some 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi\subset\omega$
\end_inset

 does influence our total belief about 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 The converse is not however true.
 A belief attributed to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\supset\varpi$
\end_inset

 does not justify any conclusions about 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our third quantity is referred to as a 
\emph on
Plausibility Function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $Pl_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}$
\end_inset

.
 Defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Pl_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\left(\omega\right)=\sum_{\omega\cap\varpi\ne\varnothing}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\varpi\right)\text{,}\label{eq: Plausibility Function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the plausibility function is interpreted as the 
\emph on
upper-probability
\emph default
 function.
 Plausibility accounts for the remaining belief supporting proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 after all of that refuting 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has been taken off the table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider all of the evidence that refutes proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 This can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\lnot\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This evidence is uncertain, and can only partially support refuting 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we have as an identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Pl_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)=Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)-Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\lnot\omega\right)=1-Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\lnot\omega\right)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our final quantity, the 
\emph on
Commonality Function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\left(\omega\right)=\sum_{\begin{gathered}\varpi\supset\omega\\
\varpi\ne\varnothing
\end{gathered}
}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\varpi\right)\text{.}\label{Commonality Function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We interpret the commonality function as the belief attributable to some
 focal element 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi$
\end_inset

 that can be reallocated to other focal elements within the FoD.
 It has special application in the combination of beliefs on a compatible
 FoD according to Dempster's rule of combination.
 It is sometimes referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fast-Fourier Transform of Belief Functions.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we can recover each of the above-four quantities — 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}},\,Bel_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}},\,Pl_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}},\,Q_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}$
\end_inset

 — from any of the others.
 This is accomplished by a set of operations referred to as 
\emph on
Möbius Transforms
\emph default
.
 We make use of one in particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)=\sum_{\varpi\subseteq\omega}\left(-1\right)^{|\omega|-|\varpi|}Bel_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\varpi\right)\label{eq: Belief-Fct Inversion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

in subsequent analysis.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl|\omega\bigr|$
\end_inset

 denotes the cardinality — the number of set members — for focal element
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that belief-attribution is preserved leads to a profound insight
 by which practical application of ToE to DA becomes possible.
 All of these operations merely 
\emph on
transfer
\emph default
 belief between focal elements.
 Belief is not destroyed or discarded.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Belief Structure on notional FoD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates this for the four quantities defined above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Illustrative Theory-of-Evidence (ToE) frame of discernment (after 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Belief Structure on notional FoD"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/FoDˣʸ.png
	lyxscale 10
	width 13.5cm
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having introduced the essential quantities by which ToE characterizes belief,
 we now summarize require operations essential to adapting ToE to the previously
-described DA methodology.
 We specifically require marginalization, vacuous extension, and combining
 a conditional bba with a prior to get a joint bba.
 Vacuous extension is particularly important for comparing information of
 different evidentiary configurations.
 When employing the information-theory concept of entropy, such comparisons
 must be based on a common FoD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marginalization is described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shafer1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Almond1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, we describe the operation here using the FoD
 illustrated in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Belief Structure on notional FoD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our focal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 span two dimensions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}=\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 We represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 as tuples, accordingly.
 For convenience, we define a projection operator, after 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Almond1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\omega\right)^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}=\big\{ x:\left(x,y\right)=\omega\subseteq\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}\big\}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega\right)^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

, we basically retain the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

's for which there is a corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\in\omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use this in marginalization.
 Our marginalized bba becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}\left(x\right)=\sum_{\begin{gathered}\left(\omega\right)^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}=x\\
\omega\in\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}
\end{gathered}
}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)\text{.}\label{eq: BBA marginalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative Marg-Ext X"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the consequences of going from 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}$
\end_inset

.
 The frame labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m\text{\underbar{\,}}\Omega^{xy}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reiterates our initial bba 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}$
\end_inset

 on FoD 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}$
\end_inset

 from Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative ToE BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The frame labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m\text{\underbar{\,}}\Omega^{x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}$
\end_inset

 on FoD 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider specifically the most-vacuous focal element, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\Bigg\{\begin{gathered}\left(x,y\right),\left(\bar{x},y\right),\\
\left(x,\bar{y}\right),\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)
\end{gathered}
\Bigg\}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding focal element in the marginalized FoD is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}=\big\{\left(x,\bar{x}\right)\big\}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\big\{\left(x,y\right),\left(\bar{x},y\right)\big\}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}=\left\{ x,\bar{x}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Also observe how the bba is reallocated from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}\mapsto\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}\left(x\right) & =m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\Big(\big\{\left(x,y\right)\big\}\Big)+m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\Big(\big\{\left(x,\bar{y}\right)\big\}\Big)\\
 & =0.1+0.1\\
 & =0.2\text{,}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}\left(\bar{x}\right) & =m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\Big(\big\{\left(\bar{x},y\right)\big\}\Big)+m_{\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\Big(\big\{\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\big\}\Big)\\
 & =0.3+0.3\\
 & =0.6\text{.}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

This is belief-transferrance provides the basis for the Smets' 
\emph on
Transferable-Belief Model
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1994,Smets2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, on which we base our ToE-based DA methodology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Illustration of marginalization along projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega\right)^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

 followed vacuous projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega\right)^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}\uparrow\mathscr{Y}}$
\end_inset

 (after 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Illustrative Marg-Ext X"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/mˣʸ↓ˣ↑ˣʸ_vacuous.png
	lyxscale 10
	width 13.5cm
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now seek to reverse the operation, through vacuous extension.
 We seek to map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\Omega}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}\mapsto\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}\uparrow\mathscr{Y}}$
\end_inset

.
 During our preceding mapping from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}\mapsto\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\Omega}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

 discarded any information in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

-dimension.
 Any extension back into that dimension must therefore be vacuous.
 Our belief-attribution cannot distinguish between 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Beliefs attributed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\Omega}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\right\} $
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \bar{x}\right\} $
\end_inset

 map in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}\uparrow\mathscr{Y}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\big\{\left(x,y\right),\left(x,\bar{y}\right)\big\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\big\{\left(\bar{x},y\right),\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\big\}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The frame labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m\underline{\:}\Omega^{xy\downarrow x\uparrow xy}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative Marg-Ext X"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 depicts this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The belief-transferrance associated with extension appears notationally
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X\uparrow\mathscr{Y}}}}\left(\omega\right)=\begin{cases}
m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}\left(x\right) & \begin{gathered}\text{if}\;\exists x\subseteq\mathscr{X}\colon\\
\qquad\omega=\left\{ x\right\} \times\left\{ y,\bar{y}\right\} 
\end{gathered}
\\
0 & \text{otherwise}\;\wedge\omega\subseteq\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}
\end{cases}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

The information in 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X\uparrow\mathscr{Y}}}}$
\end_inset

 exactly corresponds to that in 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X}}}$
\end_inset

.
 It has merely been redistributed — transferred — to a 
\emph on
minimally-extended
\emph default
 FoD whose span now includes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 However, we can no longer resolve between focal elements in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

-dimension.
 Such extensions are alternatively referred to as 
\emph on
cylindrical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Decision Analysis Using the Theory of Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although basic-belief assignment over a frame of discernment provide for
 a rich expression of uncertainty, the decision analysis employing the Howard-Ra
iffa methodology requires expression in terms of traditional Bayesian belief
 functions.
 Specifically, we must assign unit-norm sets of conditional and marginal
 probabilities to edges emanating from chance nodes in a decision tree.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the pattern.
 Two approaches have been offered.
 We review these here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Smets developed a Transferable-Belief Model (TBM) formulation of ToE for
 decision analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1994,Smets2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The TBM formulation defines a 
\emph on
Pignistic Transformation
\emph default
 involving a 
\emph on
Betting Frame
\emph default
.
 The betting fame is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Bet_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\left(\omega\right)=\sum_{\begin{gathered}\omega\in\varpi\\
\varpi\subseteq\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}
\end{gathered}
}\dfrac{m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\varpi\right)}{\bigl|\varpi\bigr|}\text{.}\label{eq: Pignistic Xform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Smets developed the Pignistic Transformation from a set of six distinct
 desiderata.
 It is grounded in subjective probabilistic concepts, and emphasizes a 
\emph on
credal-pignistic
\emph default
 link.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subsequently, Cobb and Shenoy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cobb2006,Jiroušek2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed an alternative approach.
 Their approach — the 
\emph on
Plausibility Transformation
\emph default
 — makes use of the Plausibility Function 
\begin_inset Formula $Pl_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}$
\end_inset

.
 The argue that the plausibility transformation is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more-consistent with the Dempster-Shafer semantics of belief-function models.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It moreover produces results under some circumstances that more-closely
 resemble expectations arising in scenarios involving Dempster's rule of
 belief-function combination 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dempster1967,Shafer1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The plausibility transformation ids defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Pl_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\big(\left\{ \omega\right\} \big)=\dfrac{Pl_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\big(\left\{ \omega\right\} \big)}{\sum_{\omega\in\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}Pl_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\big(\left\{ \omega\right\} \big)}\text{.}\label{eq: Plausibility Transformation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is effectively the normalization of the Plausibility Function — or
 upper probability — over the singleton (atomic) focal elements in the frame
 of discernment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The arguments about relative advantages of each technique appear arcane.
 Sufficient experience has not yet been accrued from which to characterize
 an empirically-derived distinction.
 The sequel proceeds using Smets' Pignistic transform (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Pignistic Xform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Information Quantification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Attributing value to information features prominently among the objectives
 of this study.
 We therefore seek to quantify it in the most-fundamental fashion possible.
 For that purpose we turn to Information Theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modern Information Theory was developed during the nascent stages of digital
 communications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shannon1948,Gallagher1968"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Claude Shannon, its most-prominent pioneer, sought a theoretical upper
 bound on the volume of information that could be pushed through a noisy
 communications channel.
 He discovered that this can be characterized using quantitative mechanisms
 closely resembling those of the statistical-theromynamics discipline from
 physics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ben-Naim2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, Shannon termed the fundamental quantity 
\emph on
entropy
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within information-quantification contexts, entropy assumes at least two
 interpretations.
 First, it bears a meaning congruent with John Maynard Keynes 
\emph on
irreducible uncertainty
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Keynes1921"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is the mirror image of Shannon's 
\emph on
channel capacity
\emph default
.
 Cover and Thomas 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cover1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 derived a corollary theorem, a 
\emph on
data-processing inequality
\emph default
.
 This theorem demonstrates that no amount of clever processing can extract
 information beyond a certain limit characteristic of a given data set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data-processing inequality is analogous to the Cramer-Rao Lower Bound
 (CRLB) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kay1993,Hogg2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 on estimation-error variance from mathematical statistics.
 Within a measurement scenario, entropy can conversely be thought-of as
 the quantity of noise-free measurements — unaccompanied by any uncertainty
 — required to achieve perfect certainty about the state of a measurand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We summarize the information-theoretic concepts required to justify our
 central conjecture about modes of information-derived differentiation.
 For instance, our generalized-decision problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Info Value"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) characterized the addition of differentiating information in terms of
 the opportunity make decision on conditioned probabilities instead of marginal
 ones.
 We develop the information-theoretic machinery to demonstrate this proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Information-Quantification for Bayesian-Belief Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a traditional probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\mapsto\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 We define its entropy as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H\big(\mathcal{P}\big)}=-\sum_{x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\mathcal{P}\left(x\right)\,\log\big(\mathcal{P}\left(x\right)\big).\label{eq: Shannon Entropy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The base of the logarithm is arbitrary.
 While studying 
\emph on
binary
\emph default
-symmetric communications channels, Shannon found a base-two logarithm convenien
t.
 The differential equations of statistical thermodynamics lead to a natural
 logarithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Analysis — as framed according to the Howard-Raiffa methodology
 — concerns itself with discrete, categorical probabilities.
 We are specifically interested in the marginal and conditional probabilities
 assigned to the graph edges emanating from chance nodes in a decision tree
 exemplified by Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This allows interesting considerations regarding the most-convenient logarithm
 base.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that a state of complete uncertainty for an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-category discrete probability distribution is assigned a value of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{\mathcal{P}}\left(\omega_{n}\right)=\frac{1}{N}\quad\forall\;\omega_{n}\in\left\{ \omega_{1},\ldots,\omega_{N}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

in a Bayesian context.
 The resulting entropy appears then as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}\big)=\log\left(N\right)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

Observe then that if we select a logarithmic base of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, then we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{P}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This motivates the interpretation of entropy as the quantity of uncertainty-fre
e propositions required to achieve compete certainty.
 If we receive 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(\omega_{\nu}\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\nu}\in\big\{\omega_{1},\ldots,\omega_{N}\big\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{P}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 results.
 Zero entropy corresponds to perfect certainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider the entropy of joint and marginal distributions.
 Without loss of generality, consider a two-dimensional categorical distribution
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}=\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}:\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}\mapsto\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Our corresponding entropy appears as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\big)=-\sum_{x\in\mathscr{X}}\sum_{y\in\mathscr{Y}}\mathcal{\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\left(x,y\right)\,\log\Big(\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(x,y\right)\Big)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

Now consider another scenario 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{I}\left(x,y\right)=\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{\mathscr{X}}}\left(x\right)\,\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are statistically independent.
 This entropy simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{I}\big) & =-\sum_{x\in\mathscr{X}}\sum_{y\in\mathscr{Y}}\mathcal{P}_{I}\left(x,y\right)\,\log\Big(\mathcal{P}\left(x,y\right)\Big)\\
 & =-\sum_{x\in\mathscr{X}}\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}\left(x\right)\,\log\Big(\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}\left(x\right)\Big)\\
 & \qquad-\sum_{y\in\mathscr{\mathscr{Y}}}\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}\left(y\right)\,\log\Big(\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}\left(y\right)\Big)
\end{alignedat}
\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Jensen's inequality we can show that in general
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{\text{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}\big)\leq\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}\big)+\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}\big)\text{.}\label{eq: Joint-versus-marginals entropy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So, in the special case in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}$
\end_inset

 are marginals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

, respectively, then the marginalization operation often discards information.
 This observation is consistent with our conjecture that differentiated
 access to information and differentiated insights reduce the uncertainty
 underlying the decisional context.
 Decision-making without the benefit of differentiated access or differentiated
 insights amounts to using marginal distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, how do we compare information associated with distinct probability
 distributions? Direct comparison of entropy numbers provides a rough approach.
 Only comparisons of entropies evaluated on the same probability-distribution
 domain are valid, however.
 A comparison of the type in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Joint-versus-marginals entropy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is only valid if in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}=\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 It would not be valid to compare 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{\text{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}\big)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\big(\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}\big)$
\end_inset

 by itself.
 The two quantities are incompatible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Kullback-Leibler
\emph default
 (KL) 
\emph on
distance
\emph default
 — also referred to as relative entropy — provides the most-direct comparison.
 The KL distance is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{D}\big(\mathcal{P}\parallel\mathcal{Q}\big)=\sum_{\omega\in\boldsymbol{\underline{\Omega}}}\mathcal{P}\left(\omega\right)\,\log\bigg(\frac{\mathcal{P}\left(\omega\right)}{\mathcal{Q}\left(\omega\right)}\bigg)\text{.}\label{eq: KL-distance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This explicitly enforces the constraint that the distributions being compared
 have the same support.
 Most-conspicuously, the quantity becomes undefined for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is zero but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Information-Quantification on Basic-Belief Assignments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information-quantification on a ToE FoD is obviously more-complicated.
 Quite-recently, Jiroušek and Shenoy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offered a definition for such an entropy.
 Their ToE entropy is comprised of two components.
 The Shannon Entropy defined in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Shannon Entropy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is the first component.
 We evaluate the Shannon entropy in the singleton focal elements in our
 frame of reference.
 In the ToE context, the Shannon entropy is evaluated on the plausibility
 transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $Pl_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}$
\end_inset

 defined in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Plausibility Transformation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), and appears as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\mathcal{H}_{S}\Big(Pl_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\Big)=-\sum_{\left\{ \omega\right\} \subset\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}}\Bigg[Pl_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\big(\left\{ \omega\right\} \big)\\
\times\log\bigg(Pl_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\big(\left\{ \omega\right\} \big)\bigg)\Bigg]\text{.}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

Jiroušek and Shenoy selected for their second component an entropy described
 by Dubois and Prade.
 This appears as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}_{d}\Big(m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\Big)=\sum_{\omega\in\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(\omega\right)\,\log\big(\bigl|\omega\bigr|\big)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

The total entropy associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}$
\end_inset

 becomes the sum of these two quantities.
 Specifically,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}\Big(m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\Big)=\mathcal{H}_{S}\Big(Pl_{P^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\Big)+\mathcal{H}_{d}\Big(m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\Big)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two things are noteworthy about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 First, it returns values of zero for singleton focal elements, whose cardinalit
y is unity.
 It therefore complements the Shannon entropy.
 A given focal element will either contribute a Shannon-entropy component,
 or a Dubois-Prade one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acceptance of the log-cardinality term is also interesting.
 Its resemblance to Smets' Pignistic transformation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Pignistic Xform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) seems noteworthy.
 It is consistent with the 
\emph on
Principle of Minimal Commitment
\emph default
 to which he devotes considerable attention in a description 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 of a key piece of machinery underlying the TBM methodology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also observe that a ToE equivalent to the KB distance is not obviously
 practical.
 Consider, for example, the illustration in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Illustrative Marg-Ext X"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bba 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}^{\downarrow\mathscr{X\uparrow\mathscr{Y}}}}$
\end_inset

 might be considered approximately equal to the case considered in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Joint-versus-marginals entropy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is particularly valid if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}\left(x\right)=\sum_{y\in\mathscr{Y}}\mathcal{P_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}\left(y\right)=\sum_{x\in\mathscr{X}}\mathcal{P_{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If we took 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{I}\left(x,y\right)=\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{X}}\left(x\right)\,\mathcal{P}_{\mathscr{Y}}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

, the outer product of the marginals, this approximately resembles marginalizati
on followed by vacuous extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under such circumstances, the Dubois-Prade entropy would take values of
 zero on focal elements for which belief had been transferred during the
 operations.
 These zero-valued contributions to the overall entropy have the affect
 of overstating the degree of certainty.
 Caution is therefore advised when considering such a comparison.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Competency-Focused Strategy Frameworks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our basic conjecture that information — and by extension decision-making—
 affords opportunities for competitive advantage insinuates us into the
 realm of strategy.
 The strategy science community tends to define its realm narrowly.
 The discipline traditionally focused on market positioning and resources
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Researchers more-recently proffered updated definitions about what constitutes
 a strategic decision.
 Leiblein, 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Leiblein2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue for complexity criteria including interdecisional, interactor, and
 intertemporal characteristics.
 Van den Steen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VanddenSteen2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggests along the same lines criteria including centrality, importance,
 capability-development, and competitiveness.
 Fully aligning decision-making to those factors awaits future consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We do briefly consider here competency-oriented frameworks for competitiveness.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Competency-FW Overlay"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates two that are particularly apropos.
 These include David Teece's 
\emph on
Dynamic-Capabilities
\emph default
 framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the 
\emph on
Adaptivity-Advantage 
\emph default
methodology by Martin Reeves 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Teece characterizes Dynamic Capabilities in terms of three-stage lifecycle.
 We use this lifecycle as the unifying structure for evaluating the relevance
 of each of the information-differentiation modes from our central conjecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We overlay Reeves' methodology — complementary to that of Teece — over the
 lifecycle.
 This alignment of frameworks, combined with their complementary perspectives,
 allow us to consider how the conjectured information-differentiation modes
 contribute in each phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As conveyed by the fade-in/fade-out representation in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Competency-FW Overlay"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the lines of demarcation between the competitive-position-lifecycle stages
 are fuzzy, as opposed to crisp.
 Cycle-stage durations and progressions may vary by industry, also.
 A framework by Suarez, 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Suarez2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 attempts to characterize industry contexts by degrees and natures of ecosystem
 volatilities.
 In the most-dynamic, Teece's three stages may actually be continuously
 recurring simultaneously.
 This complexities remain for subsequent consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An attempt to assign distinct conjectural modes of information to individual
 competitive-lifecycle phases appears in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Competency-FW Overlay"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We therefore cursorily describe how each mode contributes to each phase.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamlett2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 covers this topic in greater detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Overlay of information-differentiation modes onto competency-oriented strategy
 frameworks of Teece 
