\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sensing Stage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Teece's 
\emph on
Sensing Stage
\emph default
 fundamentally focuses on identifying opportunities to assert new market
 positions and identifying new resource needs.
 New market positions could pertain to material or etherial business objectives.
 We align Reeves' 
\emph on
Signal Advantage
\emph default
 to the sensing stage.
 The framework describes cultivation of organizational-epistemic competencies
 for sensing, rather than the act of sensing itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Activities in the sensing stage of the competitive lifecycle place a premium
 on differentiated insights and differentiated access, as well.
 The insights mode seems particularly important in creating new markets.
 Would-be disrupters (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2004,Christensen2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) attempting to encroach upon incumbent market space see and act upon the
 latters' vulnerabilities.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bryce2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 contains a playbook for disrupters and other insurgents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Market-space incumbents usually enjoy differentiated access based on their
 established positions.
 Powerful, new information-centered operating models have emerged since
 Porter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Drucker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 separately described the progressive centrality of information's importance
 to the economy.
 Platform operators (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VanAlstyne2016,Iansiti2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) harvest deep insights about market-transaction counterparties through
 the formers' roles as orchestrators of transactions.
 They enjoy the benefit of formidable information asymmetries.
 This translates into a greater likelihood of recognizing new marketplace
 opportunities than would-be insurgents experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Connected-systems business models — sometimes referred to as 
\emph on
Internet of Things
\emph default
 — also create pronounced information asymmetries for incumbents (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter2014,Porter2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 These models — with their internal and expectation realizations from an
 organizational perspective — involve extensive instrumentation of products,
 pipelines, and systems.
 This generates voluminous data for mining.
 The associated information is typically proprietary, affording access advantage
s to owners of the systems that generate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Seizing Stage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Teece 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 defines the 
\emph on
Seizing Stage
\emph default
 from an incumbent's perspective.
 It involves agilely reconfiguring existing resources in order to exploit
 a new opportunity.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 summarizes distinguishing characteristics allowing organizations to successfull
y pull this off.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Informationally, ability to act involves a strong organizational-learning
 component in addition to adaptivity and dynamism.
 Perhaps all of these attributes exist in concert.
 Considerable research describes inhibitors to such learning.
 Drennel and March 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Denrell2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studied risk-aversion — a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot-stove
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 affect — as an inhibitor to learning.
 Pisano 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pisano2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 makes passing mention of indiscriminate 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

learning
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the wrong things by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

innovative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cultures.
 Groysberg, 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Groysberg2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 constructed a framework characterizing organizational cultures.
 Different cultural styles, obviously, better lend themselves to seizing
 than others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Threat-Management Stage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marketplace positions, once captured, must be defended.
 Threat-management involves aspects of both the sensing and the seizing
 stages.
 Sensing provides insights into vulnerabilities and new opportunities.
 It involves overcoming biases such as confirmation biases and endowment
 affects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kahneman2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to formulate a clear view of the environment.
 Inhibitors such as those described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Denrell2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pisano2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 become vulnerabilities in themselves.
 Vulnerabilities exploitable by would-be disruptors (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2004,Christensen2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and other insurgents (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bryce2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) must be identified and remediated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ability-to-act differentiation takes on two aspects.
 The first is competent management of the existing market position (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sadun2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Operational effectiveness — particularly in complex contexts — remains
 difficult to replicate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reconfiguring existing resources in response to a threat is however often
 difficult for incumbents to manage.
 This can involve painful decisions to cannibalize existing revenue streams
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wessel2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 From a behavioral-economics perspective, this requires overcoming endowment
 affects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Case Study
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now employ a simple decision-analysis case study to demonstrate concepts
 related to our central conjecture.
 First analyzed by Strat 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Strat1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the case involves analyzing a decision about a petroleum-extraction project.
 Strat established a baseline using a traditional Bayesian DA approach.
 He then applied a ToE-based approach.
 Smets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 subsequently revisited the problem using his TBM methodology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we reproduce and extend the previous work.
 Our extensions look at the case from different angles in order to corroborate
 our central conjecture about differentiation modes based on information.
 This includes looking deeper into the results to understand specifically
 how additional information shifts the differentiations between outcomes.
 We conduct a parameter study to demonstrate the relationship between the
 value of information and its underlying uncertainty.
 We show how reduced uncertainty leads to higher informational value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our extension of Smets' results from the Transferable-Belief Model (TBM)
 provide a basis for a point-comparison with the Bayesian approach.
 Specifically, we compare entropies according to Jiroušek's and Shenoy's
 approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 according to a common frame of discernment.
 We thereby demonstrate that the ToE representation leads to a lower degree
 of certainty.
 We again seek to illuminate how that difference shows up in the distributions
 of final outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameters of the case study appear to be stylized and contrived.
 They nonetheless provide the mechanism to develop logical machinery that
 can subsequently be applied to more-realistic problems.
 They moreover support thought experiments by which we validate the premises
 of our central conjecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Decision Analysis Based on the Traditional Bayesian Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are considering an oil-extraction project.
 We must decided whether or not to drill a new oil well.
 We face two dimensions of uncertainty related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, the state of the oil field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 the productivity of an oil will drilled there.
 Three yield states 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 — Dry well with no production, a Trickle well producing a modicum of output,
 and a Gusher producing high volumes — are possible.
 The net-present value (NPV) of revenues from these states are $0, $120,000,
 and $270,000, respectively.
 A well costs $70,000 to drill.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may at a cost of $10,000 elect to perform a seismic survey.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

test
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reveals information about the geological structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 of the field.
 The likely yield depends in part on this structure.
 A field lacking structure — 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

None
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 — is likely to be porous.
 Petroleum crude is unlikely to have accumulated under such circumstances.
 Accumulation may have occurred if the structure is is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Open
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Closed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 structure is conducive to a petroleum reservoir.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, we face two decisions: Whether to test 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}=\left\{ \text{Yes},\text{No}\right\} $
\end_inset

, and whether to drill 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}=\left\{ \text{Yes},\text{No}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We may make our decision 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

 with or without knowledge of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, the oil-field structure.
 The adaptation of our generalized optimum decision rule (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) becomes therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}^{opt}\big)=\\
=\arg\max_{\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}},\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\big)}\bigg\{\Big({\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
h\in\mathscr{H}\\
s\in\mathcal{S}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(h,s;\,\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}\big)\Big)\\
-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}},\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\big)\bigg\}\text{.}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

Observe that our return is independent of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 of the oil field.
 Moreover, it only depends on decision 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

 whether or not to drill.
 If we test 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\ni\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}$
\end_inset

, then our probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\big(h,s;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}}\big)$
\end_inset

 remains a joint distribution in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}\times\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 We get to make our decision using probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}}\mid s\big)$
\end_inset

 conditioned on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we do not test — 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\ni\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}$
\end_inset

 — then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\big(h,s;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}\big)=\mathcal{P}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}\big)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, our probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 becomes independent of the oil-field structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Our outcome probabilities for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 are based on the marginal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(h\right)=\sum_{s\in\mathcal{S}}\mathcal{P}\left(h,s\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Our prior information-theory discussion leads us to expect the corresponding
 reduced degree of certainty will lead to lower expected net returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also observe that the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the decision whether or not to drill 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

.
 It characterizes probabilistic outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

, which in turn influence the return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

.
 In our general case (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Decision"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) - (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Return"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we abstracted our set of decisions into a single, opaque set.
 In a specific scenario, we partition our decision set into subsets influencing
 our knowledge of the probability state, and those merely influencing outcomes.
 In some cases distinct decisions may fit into both categories.
 Our scenario here is clearer when we separate them out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our two returns — distinguished by whether or not we conduct the geophysical
 survey 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}$
\end_inset

 — become from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Opt Return"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\mathcal{R}^{\text{test}}={\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
h\in\mathscr{H}\\
s\in\mathcal{S}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(h,s;\,\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\\
-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}\big)
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\mathcal{R}^{\text{no test}}={\displaystyle \sum_{\begin{array}{c}
h\in\mathscr{H}\\
s\in\mathcal{S}
\end{array}}\mathcal{P}\big(h;\,,\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}\big)\:}\mathcal{R}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}}\big)\Big)\\
-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}\big)\text{.}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Info Value"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\text{test result}}$
\end_inset

 of the information from the seismic survey appears as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{V}_{\text{test result}}=\mathcal{R}^{\text{test}}-\mathcal{R}^{\text{no test}}-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}\big)\text{.}\label{eq: Bayesian Case Info Value}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Recall that our key question is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How much is the information worth?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 We therefore subtract the cost of its acquisition out of our calculation
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\text{test result}}$
\end_inset

 .
 Our return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^{\text{test}}$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}$
\end_inset

 is calculated net 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}\big)$
\end_inset

, which includes the decision-acquisition cost.
 To explicitly see the information's value, we segregate out its acquisition
 cost.
 Also, we obtain an expected marginal return on information as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_{\text{test result}}=\dfrac{\mathcal{R}^{\text{test}}-\mathcal{R}^{\text{no test}}}{\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}\big)-\mathcal{C}\big(\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}^{\text{opt}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}\big)}\text{.}\label{eq: Bayesian Test Marg Return Info}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the presence of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Test/No-Test
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 decision 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}}$
\end_inset

 makes this resemble a differentiated-access scenario.
 Were this a competitive situation, one market participant might select
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\ni\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}$
\end_inset

, while another operates in a scenario characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\ni\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
If
\emph default
 information from the test produces a scenario in which conditioning 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D},\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}}\mid s\big)$
\end_inset

 is materially advantageous to with respect to the marginal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\big(h;\,\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}},\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}\big)$
\end_inset

, then participants electing to test enjoy an informational asymmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gives the probabilistic structure of the case study.
 This is a joint probability structure.
 The resulting conditional probabilities appear in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Conditionals"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We see for this scenario, the conditional probabilities in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Conditionals"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 differentiate much more than than the joints.
 For another perspective, Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Marginal Outers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 contains the outer product of the marginals from Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This begins to reveal the relative loss of information due to marginalization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can quantitatively characterize this in two ways.
 First, we have the Kullback-Leibler distance (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: KL-distance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The KL distance between distributions in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Marginal Outers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the outer product marginals of the former, is 0.144 nats.
 We use the natural logarithm, here, for entropy calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, we might consider the sums of the diagonal elements of the
 two tables.
 This is loosely related to the categorical-statistical concepts of sensitivity
 and sensitivity.
 The sum of the diagonals in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is 0.52, while the sum is 0.358 for Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Marginal Outers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 contains 1.45 times more of its population in the diagonals than Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Marginal Outers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We employ these in our subsequent parameter study in an attempt to gain
 insight into information and value.
\end_layout

