\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Oil-Well Bayes Dec Tree"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, now, depicts the decision-tree framing according to the Howard-Raiffa
 methodology.
 This is Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Gen Decision-Tree Framing "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with the probabilities applied to the graph vertices emanating from the
 chance nodes, and the expected net returns propagated back to the original
 decision node.
 Our first decision is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}$
\end_inset

, whether conduct the seismic survey.
 We apply marginal utilities to graph edges emanating from the left-most,
 circular chance nodes.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\ni\mathfrak{t}=\text{No}$
\end_inset

 scenario we operate without information about the structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 of the oil field.
 Consequently, we apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 from the marginal column in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 chance node.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}\ni\mathfrak{t}=\text{Yes}$
\end_inset

 scenario apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 from Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

's marginal row to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 chance node.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Decision-tree framing for the oil-drilling case study employing Strats'
 Bayesian uncertainty structure of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 (After 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Oil-Well Bayes Dec Tree"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/190430 Oil-Drilling Decision-Tree —  Strat Traditional.png
	lyxscale 15
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conditional probabilities get applied to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 chance nodes to the right of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 chance node.
 We propagate the expected net returns right-to-left as probability-weighted
 net returns.
 Our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Drill/No-Drill
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 decision nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}$
\end_inset

 are the conditional decisions.
 We elect to drill or not to drill based on the expected net returns of
 the nodes to the right of each.
 The decision to drill 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}\ni\mathfrak{d}=\text{Yes}$
\end_inset

 represents the optimum decision in all cases except for one.
 If the seismic survey reveals no structure, the likelihood of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dry
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 well is is high enough for us to have an expected loss.
 We therefore select 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{D}}\ni\mathfrak{d}=\text{No}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What then is the value of the information obtained from the seismic survey
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{T}}$
\end_inset

? We see that the expected net return given testing is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^{\text{test}}=\$22,500$
\end_inset

.
 The return without testing is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^{\text{no test}}=\$20,000$
\end_inset

.
 The optimum decision then is to test and proceed with drilling if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\ni s\ne\text{None}$
\end_inset

.
 From (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Bayesian Case Info Value"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), the information value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\text{test result}}=\$12,500$
\end_inset

.
 Paying $10,000 to receive $12,500 appears to be a bargain.
 Moreover, the expected marginal return on information from the test from
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Bayesian Test Marg Return Info"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\mathcal{M}_{\text{test result}} & =\frac{\$2,500}{\$10,000}\\
 & =25\%
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

for a geophysical-survey cost of $10,000.
 In this case, the return is quite high.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A parameter study allows us to explore how the value of information relates
 to uncertainty.
 To proceed, we need a joint distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(s,h\right)$
\end_inset

 over which we can exercise simple control.
 We set aside considerations here about phenomenological accuracy.
 This is a thought experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do we accomplish this? One approach involves constraining one of our
 marginals and specifying all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(s,h\right)$
\end_inset

 using a single parameter.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Synthetic Bayesian joints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides just such a mechanism.
 We sweep our 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 factor over a range of values.
 For each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 we solve for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{1},a_{2}a_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 using the linear equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \alpha & \alpha^{2}\\
\alpha & 1 & \alpha\\
\alpha^{2} & \alpha & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{1}\\
a_{2}\\
a_{3}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
m_{1}\\
m_{2}\\
m_{3}
\end{array}\right)\text{.}\label{eq: Synthetic pdf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For this analysis we want 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is very small, the matrix is mostly-diagonal.
 This amounts to a case in which the expected outcome conditioned on a geologica
l state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(h\mid s\right)$
\end_inset

 will be high for one 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Our test is very-informative.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 approaches unity, conditioning on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 looses its ability to discriminate between states in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To elaborate, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ll1$
\end_inset

 our uncertainty is dominated by the marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ m_{1},m_{2},m_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This represents our irreducible uncertainty (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Keynes1921"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) for this scenario.
 The uncertainty in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(h,s\right)$
\end_inset

, which has substantial discriminate power.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 becomes larger, the uncertainty in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(h,s\right)$
\end_inset

 comes to dominate.
 When it becomes sufficiently large, uncertainty in the marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ m_{1},m_{2},m_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 becomes diminsishingly significant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Approach to synthesizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(s,h\right)$
\end_inset

 for purposes of parameter study.
\end_layout

\end_inset


