\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayes-Framing Parameter Study"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows just such an analysis.
 Employing the scheme from Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Synthetic Bayesian joints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we sweep 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 from 0.1 to 0.5 in steps of 0.025.
 A quick validity check shows us values from Strat's point study — K-B distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 0.11, ratio of diagonals 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 1.45, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\text{test result}}\approx\$2,500$
\end_inset

 — fall close to these curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, these results corroborate our conjecture about the relationship
 between uncertainty and value of information.
 The unequivocal trend in this analysis holds that increasing certainty
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(h,s\right)$
\end_inset

 increases the value of the associated information.
 Reduced uncertainty increases the predictability of outcomes.
 All parameters point in that direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, the point-parameters from the baseline case defined by Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayesian Oil-Field Struc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are characterized by a relatively high degree of uncertainty.
 The associated parameters fall in the lower-left-hand region of the space
 for which calculations in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Bayes-Framing Parameter Study"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 appear.
 We assume that the given probability structure is stylized to illustrate
 the methodology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Parameter study demonstrating relationship between Bayesian-uncertainty
 structure and value of information.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Bayes-Framing Parameter Study"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Box Sync/X-Enterprise Share/Belief Functions/Bayes_Param_Study.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 17cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see at the boundaries of the parameter study that the value of the informatio
n can swing negative.
 What might be occurring here? It seems that the information from the geophysica
l survey is of such low quality that its use is counterproductive.
 The information serves to avoid the case in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\ni s=\text{None}$
\end_inset

.
 Some probability of a favorable outcome exists in this scenario.
 If we cannot however distinguish between favorable and unfavorable outcomes
 with sufficient precision, then using the information is counterproductive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Decision Analysis Using Theory of Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now turn to the ToE-based framing of the decision case study.
 As is obvious from the previous section, ToE analysis is considerably more-comp
lex than Bayesian analysis.
 This should be clear from equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Unit-norm BBA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Belief-Fct Inversion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 That we assign partial belief should also contribute to this recognition.
 The payoffs however arise from a more-complete characterization of uncertainty.
 Marrying ToE to information modeling from Information Economics offers
 promise of tighter linkage to valuation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now walk through for ToE decision analysis a procedure that resembles
 that performed for the Bayesian analysis above.
 We begin with basic-belief assignments (bbas) on our frame of discernment.
 We must transform our bbas into Bayesian probabilities.
 We accomplish that using the pignistic transform (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Pignistic Xform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This gives us the bba-derived Bayesian probabilities with which we can
 populate the decision tree.
 We attempt moreover to characterize the degree of uncertainty and to compare
 it with the Bayesian approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Conditional BBAs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 contains our starting point.
 This contains the bba assignments on our frame of discernment.
 We elicit this information either through subject-matter experts or through
 analytical approaches when possible.
 As with the real world, ambiguity is inescapable.
 This elicitation approach accounts for that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, the contents of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Conditional BBAs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are conditional bbas.
 The are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conditioned
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the geological structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Adopting Smets' notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the degree of belief attributed to the proposition that outcome
 
\begin_inset Formula $h\subseteq\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 is correct given evidence that the geophysical structure is characterized
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\subseteq\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that both 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are set objects within their respective frames of discernment.
 We see in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Conditional BBAs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that many of our beliefs are vacuously attributed to combinations of propositio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\left\{ \text{None}\right\} \big]\big(\left\{ \text{Dr},\text{Tr}\right\} \big)=0.4$
\end_inset

 indicates that, were we presented with certain evidence of the geological
 structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\supseteq s=\left\{ \text{None}\right\} $
\end_inset

, we would belief that the likelihood is 0.4 that the outcome will be either
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dry
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 well or a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Trickle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Our evidence does not support the proposition that one or the other is
 more or less likely.
 Unless we received additional evidence, we at best can merely say that
 one or the other is valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Conditional basic-belief assignments 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 for Theory-of-Evidence Transferable-Belief Method (TBM).
 (From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Strat1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Conditional BBAs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

