\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Getting the marginal bbas on 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[m^{\mathcal{S}}\big]$
\end_inset

 shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Conditional BBAs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 involves a nontrivial exercise.
 Smets described the technique at length in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describing his 
\emph on
Disjunctive Rule of Combination
\emph default
.
 These values can be obtained through a four-step method implied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 47"
key "Smets2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We first translate each 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

into its corresponding Belief Function 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 using (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Belief Function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Secondly, we obtain an intermittent quantity
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Bel\big[\mathcal{X}\big]\left(h\right)=\prod_{s\in\mathcal{X}}Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel\big[\mathcal{X}\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 is essentially a joint belief function on sets of structural states instead
 of distinct ones.
 We next get the marginal belief function by applying our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prior
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathcal{S}}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\Big[m^{\mathcal{S}}\Big]\left(h\right)=\sum_{\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathcal{S}}m^{\mathcal{S}}\left(\mathcal{X}\right)\,Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\mathcal{X}\big]\left(h\right)\;\forall h\subseteq\mathscr{H}\text{.}\label{eq: DRC-Marginal Belief Fct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We finally recover 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\Big[m^{\mathcal{S}}\Big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\Big[m^{\mathcal{S}}\Big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 using the Möbius-transform inversion (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Belief-Fct Inversion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further analysis of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 may yield more-direct transformations.
 Also, simply multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathcal{S}}\left(\mathcal{X}\right)\,Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\mathcal{X}\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: DRC-Marginal Belief Fct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) without evaluating the summation produces the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

joint
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 belief function 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel^{\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}}\left(h,s\right)$
\end_inset

 on the frame of discernment 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\Omega}}}}=\mathscr{X}\times\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The summation over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 accomplishes a marginalization along the lines of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: BBA marginalization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A reiteration of our notation will probably help to clarify things.
 We said previously that 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the belief assigned to some proposition about our outcome associated
 with a focal element 
\begin_inset Formula $h\subseteq\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 given certain evidence that the geological structure is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\subseteq\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We in fact did not receive certain evidence about the geological structure.
 We received a basic-belief assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathcal{S}}\left(s\right)\;\forall s\subseteq\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Our conditional bba 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\Big[m^{\mathcal{S}}\Big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 then represents our belief about the proposition for a given outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $h\subseteq\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 given the aggregate evidence represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathcal{S}}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Cond-Marg Belief on H"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides graphical depictions of belief structure on our outcome frame
 of discernment 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

.
 It includes for each column in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Conditional BBAs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the bbas 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

, the corresponding belief functions 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

, and the plausibility functions 
\begin_inset Formula $Pl^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Its study is instructive for many reasons.
 First, one enjoys a visual glimpse of how the beliefs are allocated.
 We see how in 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

, beliefs provided initially by 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[s\big]\left(h\right)$
\end_inset

 flow from most-specific towards most-vacuous.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\left\{ \text{None}\right\} \big]\big(\left\{ \text{Dr}\right\} \big)$
\end_inset

 influences our beliefs 
\begin_inset Formula $Bel^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\left\{ \text{None}\right\} \big]\big(\left\{ \text{Dr},\text{Gu}\right\} \big)$
\end_inset

.
 But belief attribution does not flow in the opposite direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plausibility functions are even-more interesting.
 In calculating plausibilities according to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Plausibility Function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we look for combinations such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\cap\varpi\ne\varnothing$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,\varpi\subseteq\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

.
 In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Conditional BBAs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we attribute finite basic belief 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\left\{ \text{None}\right\} \big]\big(\left\{ \text{Dr},\text{Tr}\right\} \big)$
\end_inset

 .
 In the plausibility calculation, this flows to 
\begin_inset Formula $Pl^{\mathscr{H}}\big[\left\{ \text{None}\right\} \big]\big(\left\{ \text{Dr}\right\} \big)$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \text{Dr},\text{Tr}\right\} \cap\left\{ \text{Dr}\right\} \ne\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

